Table 22.1 illustrates the cash flows at the three relevant times: the initial trade date, $(\tau=0)$ ), the evaluation date, $t.$ , and the [expiration date](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Risk%20Neutral%20Pricing%20of%20Options.md), $T_{\mathbf{\delta}}$ . Adapting Equation (22.5) for the condition at time $t$ instead of time 0, we have the price of the new [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) as  
$$
F_{t}(T)=S_{t}(1+r)^{\tau_{t}}.
$$  

Using this result in Equation (22.6), we can then restate the value equation as  
$$
V_{t}\big[F_{0}(T)\big]=S_{t}-\frac{F_{0}(T)}{(1+r)^{\tau_{t}}}.
$$  

Or essentially, the current spot price minus the present value of the original [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md). Note that if we set $t=0$ or $t=T$ in Equation (22.7), we obtain Equations (22.1) and (22.2):  
$$
\begin{array}{l}{t=0:V_{0}\big[F_{0}(T)\big]=S_{0}-F_{0}(T)/(1+r)^{\tau}=S_{0}-S_{0}=0}\\ {t=T:V_{T}\big[F_{0}(T)\big]=S_{T}-F_{0}(T)/(1+r)^{0}=S_{T}-F_{0}(T).}\end{array}
$$  

For example, assume at time 0 a one-year [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) was entered at $\$25[F_{0}(T)]$ . You have been tasked with determining the fair value of this contract after nine months (time $t$ ). At time $t$ , we know the underlying instrument priced is $\$26$ and the interest rate is $3.902\%$ (annual compounding). In this case we know the price of a new [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) is  
$$
F_{t}(T)=S_{t}(1+r)^{\tau_{t}}=26(1+0.03902)^{0.25}=26.25.
$$  

Further, the value of the initial [long forward](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%203%20Swaps-%20Financial%20Instruments/Forward%20Rates%20Agreement.md) contract at time $t$ is  
$$
V_{t}\big[F_{0}(T)\big]=\frac{F_{t}(T)-F_{0}(T)}{(1+r)^{\tau_{t}}}=\frac{26.25-25}{(1+0.03902)^{0.25}}=\S1.238.
$$  

Note that the contract, which had a zero value nine months earlier, is now worth a positive value. Intuitively, its value has increased because it is the obligation to buy an asset that has since increased in value.  

# 22.1.2 Forward Contracts and Options  

Now, let us tie forward contracts back to options. First, note that because a [long position](../../Derivatives/Part%20I%20-%20Forwards%20and%20Futures/Chapter%204%20-%20Futures:%20Hedging%20and%20Speculation.md) in the asset, hedged with a [short forward contract](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forward%20Contracts%20on%20Exchange%20Rates.md), can create a riskless position or essentially a risk-free bond, it follows that a position in the asset can be replicated by a [long position](../../Derivatives/Part%20I%20-%20Forwards%20and%20Futures/Chapter%204%20-%20Futures:%20Hedging%20and%20Speculation.md) in a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) and a [long position](../../Derivatives/Part%20I%20-%20Forwards%20and%20Futures/Chapter%204%20-%20Futures:%20Hedging%20and%20Speculation.md) in a risk-free bond. Recall that [put-call parity](../../7.%20Black%20Scholes%20Model.md) states that  
$$
p_{0}+S_{0}=c_{0}+\frac{X}{\left(1+r\right)^{\tau}}.
$$  

Given Equation (22.3), we can substitute into [put-call parity](../../7.%20Black%20Scholes%20Model.md) for $S_{0}$ and obtain  
$$
p_{0}+\frac{F_{0}(T)}{\left(1+r\right)^{\tau}}=c_{0}+\frac X{\left(1+r\right)^{\tau}}.
$$  

As such, Equation (22.10) expresses the relationships among the put price, the call price, the option [exercise price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2012%20-%20Derivatives/Options.md), and the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md). Note that because we are free to choose the [exercise price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2012%20-%20Derivatives/Options.md) of the options, we could set the [exercise price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2012%20-%20Derivatives/Options.md) to the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md). Then $F_{0}(T)=X$ , and from Equation (22.10), we would have the put and call prices equal to each other.  

# 22.1.3 Some Additional Facts on Forward Contracts  

Finally, let us learn a few more important facts about [forward contract pricing](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%203%20Swaps-%20Financial%20Instruments/Swaps%20Types.md). We have said that a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) does not involve any exchange of money between buyer and seller at the start; hence, the value of the contract is zero at the start. This is the standard case, but it is not absolutely mandatory. The buyer and seller of a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) can set the price at whatever [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) they want. These types of contracts are called [off-market forward](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%205%20Options%20on%20Prices%20and%20Hedge-Based%20Valuation/Options%20and%20Forwards%20Risk%20Sharing%20and%20Put-Call.md) contracts. First, take another look at Equation (22.3), which is repeated here:  
$$
F_{0}(T)=S_{0}(1+r)^{\tau}.
$$  

Suppose the parties set $F_{0}(T)$ to a value higher than the RHS. Now, let us see what happens. We first restate the value Equation, (22.7), with $t=0$ :  
$$
V_{0}\big[F_{0}(T)\big]=S_{0}-\frac{F_{0}(T)}{\left(1+r\right)^{\tau}}.
$$  

If the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) is set to the formula price, Equation (22.3), this value goes to zero, as we have shown. But if the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) is set higher than the formula price, then the value becomes negative. A negative value contract means that the seller must pay the buyer the value at the start. Let us think about this. If the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) is too high, the buyer has agreed to pay too much at time $T$ for the asset. Hence, the seller has the advantage and must compensate the buyer for this additional value at time 0. If the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) is set lower than the formula price, then the value in the above equation becomes positive. A positive value contract means that the buyer must pay the seller the contract value at the start. In this case, the buyer will be paying too little at time $T$ and must compensate the seller for this additional value at time 0.  

Finally, let us note several additional characteristics of forward contracts. Typical forward contracts contain provisions that allow either party to request a settlement of the other. That is, the contract can be terminated early. Suppose the long holds a position that has a value, as calculated in the manner shown in Equation (22.7), of $\$1.5$ million. The long and the short could, thus, terminate the contract before expiration by having the short pay the long $\$1.5$ million. If the value were negative, the long would pay the short. Either party can request an early termination, but typically one party is a dealer and dealers do not usually request early termination, because they exist to serve the needs of their clients and not to impose their own needs on their clients. The counterparty, who is usually an end user, would ordinarily be the one to request an early termination.  

Forward contracts can also be written to specify that at expiration the contract calls for physical delivery of the asset or an alternative procedure called [cash settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2016/Swaptions.md). Suppose, for example, that the buyer holds a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) on two million barrels of crude oil with a [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) of $\$70$ a barrel. Now, let us say we are at expiration and the price of crude oil is $\$75$ a barrel. A physical delivery contract would result in the short delivering two million barrels of oil to the long, who would pay the short $\$70$ a barrel. So the long benefits by acquiring two million barrels at $\$5$ per barrel below the market price. Alternatively, a cash-settled contract would result in the short simply paying the long $\$10$ million. By settling in cash, the two parties can avoid the high transaction costs of handling the oil.  

Forward contracts are subject to default. Technically the dealer or the end user could default. In deriving these [pricing](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md) formulas, we have not taken default into account, because that is a subset of the subject of [credit risk](../../../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md). Some forward contracts are processed through a clearinghouse and are subject to [margin requirements](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2010/Case%20Study%20Mf%20Globals%20Repo-To-Maturity%20Trades.md) and periodic settlements, which is the standard process used in [futures contracts](../../Mathematics%20of%20the%20Financial%20Markets.md), as we explain next.  

# 22.2 PRICING FUTURES CONTRACTS  

A [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract is effectively a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) that is resettled every day. That is, at the end of the day, the clearinghouse of the exchange determines an official settlement price, which is an average of the last few trades of the day. The change in the settlement price from the previous day is then credited to the party that gained and charged to the party that lost. Thus, if the settlement price increased (decreased), the holders of long (short) positions would be credited the gain and the holders of short (long) positions would be charged the loss. This process is called marking-to-market and, sometimes, the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md). It effectively results in gains and losses being collected and charged in smaller amounts over shorter periods of time than in the case of forward contracts, whereby the contract is completely settled at expiration. The process of settling daily reduces the [credit risk](../../../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md). In fact, [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) exchanges guarantee that no one will fail to be paid because of the default of the opposite party. This guarantee has been absolutely fulfilled, because no party has ever lost money on any [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) exchange in the world due to default of the counterparty. The exchange, through its clearinghouse, has always either collected the money or paid up itself.  

# 22.2.1 Daily Settlement and Futures Prices with Constant Interest Rates  

The [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) results in a difference in the pattern of cash flows to a holder of a [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract in comparison to that of a holder of a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md). As it turns out, there are some circumstances in which this difference has no economic effect, and in most cases, it is likely to have no material impact. But let us start by seeing what the effect is, however small it might turn out to be. This work draws on Jarrow and Oldfield (1981) and Cox, Ingersoll, and Ross (1981).  

Let us set up the problem by denoting the [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) at time $t$ for a contract expiring at time $T$ as $f_{t}(T)$ . [Futures contracts](../../Mathematics%20of%20the%20Financial%20Markets.md) trade on a [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) exchange and are, therefore, updated throughout the trading session. Our first important result is the convergence of the [futures price at expiration](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Cost%20of%20Delivery%20and%20the%20Final%20Settlement%20Pric.md) to the spot price. That is, a [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract that is created an instant before expiration will be priced at the spot price, because it will immediately expire and result in delivery of the spot asset, thus,  
$$
f_{T}(T)=S_{T}.
$$  

Now let us take a look at how one would value a [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract. Suppose on day $t$ , the settlement price for the previous day was $f_{t-1}(T)$ . Now, here at the end of day $t$ the price is $f_{t}(T)$ . The accumulated value is $\ensuremath{f_{t}}(T)-\ensuremath{f_{t-1}}(T).\operatorname{Sc}$ , at this point, an instant before the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md), the value of the [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract is  

Before the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md),  
$$
\nu_{t}(T)=f_{t}(T)-f_{t-1}(T).
$$  

That is, the value is simply the price change from the previous settlement. As soon as the market closes, the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) at day $t$ will occur. If the previous value is positive (negative), the profit will be credited (charged) to the holder of the [long position](../../Derivatives/Part%20I%20-%20Forwards%20and%20Futures/Chapter%204%20-%20Futures:%20Hedging%20and%20Speculation.md), and the loss will be charged (credited) to the holder of the short position. After the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md), the value reverts to zero,  

After the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md),  
$$
\nu_{t}(T)=0.
$$  

In effect, the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) means that the contract is terminated and rewritten at the new settlement price. This is why we described a [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract as a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) that is settled and rewritten every day.  

Now, let us take a look at when forward prices would equal [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) prices. Table 22.2 illustrates the pattern of cash flows from day 1 through day $T.$ , the expiration.  

We want to know if the original [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md), $F_{0}(T)$ , would equal the original [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md), $f_{0}(T)$ . First, let us step back to one day prior to expiration, in which the [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) would be $f_{t-1}(T)$ . One day later the contract will expire and effectively conduct its last [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md). A [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) created on that day will also settle one day later. Hence, the two contracts will have the same [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) one day later; thus, the forward and [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) prices will be the same,  

One day prior to expiration,  
$$
f_{T-1}(T)=F_{T-1}(T).
$$  

Stepping back one further day to $T-2$ , we can show that if the interest rate on day $t$ is known on day $t-1$ , the [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) on day $t$ would equal the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) on day $t$ . Let us assume that the interest rate, $r$ , is constant from day to day, a common assumption in derivative [pricing](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md) theory.4 Let us construct the following strategy: Buy one [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) at the price $F_{T-2}(T)$ and sell $1/(1+r)$ [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) at the price $f_{T-2}(T)$ . At the end of day $T-1$ , we generate no [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) on the [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) because it is not settled daily and has one more day to expiration. Through its [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md), however, the [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) will produce a [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) of $\mathsf{\bar{-}}\big[f_{T-1}(T)-f_{T-2}(T)\big]$ times $1/(1+r)$ contracts. If this amount is negative, let us borrow the funds at the rate $r$ for one day. If it is positive, we invest the funds at the rate $r$ for one day. By borrowing or investing the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md), we avoid having to put up or withdraw funds on a day-to-day basis. One day later, which is expiration, the [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) amount at $T-1$ plus one day’s interest paid or received will be $-\left[f_{T-1}(T)-f_{T-2}(T)\right].$ . In addition, the final [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) will be $-\big[f_{T}(T)-f_{T-1}(T)\big]$ . Adding these two amounts gives a total [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) at $T$ of $-\Bigl[\dot{f}_{T-1}(T)\dot{-}f_{T-2}(T)\Bigr]-\Bigl[\dot{f}_{T}(T)-\dot{f}_{T-1}(T)\Bigr]=\dot{f}_{T-2}(T)-\dot{f}_{T}(T)=\dot{f}_{T-2}(T)-{S_{T-1}}(T),$ . This is the same [cash flow](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) as on a two-day [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md). We could successively create [forwards and futures](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Forward%20and%20Futures%20Contracts.md) further back and similarly demonstrate that the cash flows would be the same. Hence, the price of a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) would equal the price of the analogous [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract. Of course, similar to [forwards](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2012%20-%20Derivatives/Forwards%20and%20Futures.md), [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) will also reflect carrying costs and any other potential benefits or costs of holding the asset.5  

